player.seasonOutlook: Brissett signed with Cleveland after spending his first six seasons with the Patriots, Colts and Dolphins. Brissett's role is that of Deshaun Watson's backup, but with Watson suspended for 11 games, he'll get an extended look as the starter. That won't necessarily translate to fantasy value, however, as he has produced one weekly finish better than 19th over the last two seasons and his two seasons as a starter have resulted in fringe QB2 output. Brissett adds some value with his legs, but he's a conservative, inefficient passer and Cleveland will almost assuredly stick with a run-heavy scheme while he's under center. He shouldn't be in lineups.

Smith re-signed with Seattle and will compete with newcomer Drew Lock for the team's starting job. Smith has played sparingly (15 appearances) during the last seven seasons, but made three starts in relief of an injured Russell Wilson in 2021. He totaled five touchdowns and threw zero INTs en route to one top-15 fantasy outing (seventh) during the span. Despite the respectable showing, Smith is now 31 years old and his best fantasy finish was 20th as a rookie back in 2013. If called upon to start, he'll have a respectable group of targets (DK Metcalf, Tyler Lockett, Noah Fant), but is unlikely to perform well enough to come anywhere close to starting consideration in fantasy. He shouldn't be drafted.

Brate is entering his ninth NFL season -- all with Tampa Bay -- though the veteran tight end hasn't been a fantasy factor in quite a while. Brate last finished a season better than 19th in 2017 (10th) and has finished 28th or worse the last two seasons while working behind Rob Gronkowski and sometimes O.J. Howard. Howard (Buffalo) and Gronkowski (retired) are both gone, of course, leaving Brate to compete with Kyle Rudolph and rookie Cade Otton. He's theoretically positioned as a fantasy sleeper considering Tampa Bay's high-scoring offense, but note that he posted a 9-88-1 receiving line on 21 targets during a six-game stretch Gronk was out/limited last season (Howard's stats were almost identical those weeks). The 30-year-old is barely worth a late-round flier.

Uzomah signed with the Jets after spending his first seven seasons with the Bengals. His production has been all over the map during his career, as he's often been a backup, but he stepped in nicely with a 43-439-3 receiving line in place of Tyler Eifert in 2018 and was finally handed a Week 1 every-down role in 2021. Uzomah responded with career-best marks in receptions, yards and touchdowns, though he failed to record his first-career top-15 fantasy campaign. The 29-year-old is a solid real-life player, but he primarily works in the short area and will defer work to fellow newcomers Tyler Conklin and Jeremy Ruckert. Uzomah is a low-ceiling, fringe TE2.

Bryant is entering his third NFL season in position for a larger role after the offseason departure of Austin Hooper. Bryant has played a hefty 952 snaps during his first two seasons, but he's been limited to 67 targets while working alongside David Njoku and Hooper. Njoku remains Cleveland's primary pass-catching tight end, but Bryant will be busy considering Cleveland had multiple tight ends on the field at the third-highest rate last season. The 24-year-old does not have standalone value, but if Njoku were to miss time, Bryant would jump into the TE2 mix and, once Deshaun Watson is under center, could potentially push for TE1 consideration. Bryant is fine dynasty hold.

Parham is back with the Chargers and enters 2022 in a very similar position as last season. Jared Cook is gone and Gerald Everett in atop the depth chart, leaving Parham to compete with second-year Tre' McKitty for situational work. Parham has posted 10-159-3 and 20-190-3 receiving lines during his two NFL campaigns. He's only 25 years old, so it's possible we've yet to see his best work, but he doesn't have any standalone value in his projected role. However, if Everett were to miss time, Parham very well could emerge as the top receiving TE in one of the league's top offenses. He's worth monitoring in deep and dynasty leagues.

Ridder was selected by Atlanta in the third round of April's draft. A four-year starter at Cincinnati, Ridder is a big, athletic QB who adds substantial value with his legs (career 409-2,822-28 rushing line). He was aggressive during a breakout 2021 campaign, posting a 9.7 aDOT, though his efficiency wasn't great (65% completion rate, 71.9 QBR). Ridder showed off his size and athleticism at the combine, checking in with class-high 10-inch hands and topping the QB leaderboard in the 40-yard dash, vertical and broad jump. Non-first-round QBs are long shots for NFL success, but Ridder has a path to significant rookie-season playing time (Marcus Mariota is Atlanta's top veteran QB) and his rushing ability could help him to some fantasy value, especially in superflex formats. He should only be drafted in dynasty and superflex leagues.

Garoppolo is expected to be traded after five seasons with the 49ers. He has always been efficient and that's reflected in his career 8.4 YPA, which is best among all qualified QBs since he was drafted in 2014. It's also reflected in his 2021 numbers, as he ranked sixth in completion percentage (68%), second in YPA (8.6) and 12th in QBR (53.0). However, none of that has translated to much fantasy success. Garoppolo is very conservative (6.9 aDOT since 2019), offers very little with his legs (192 yards in 63 career games) and has missed substantial time due to injury. In turn, he's yet to provide a single top-12 fantasy campaign. Now 30 years old, Garoppolo is a fringe QB2, at best.

Darnold is expected to compete with third-round rookie Matt Corral for the Panthers' backup QB gig behind Baker Mayfield this season. The start of the Darnold era in Carolina exceeded all expectations. The former Jet found the end zone 10 times during his first four games and was fantasy's No. 5 QB during the span. The wheels fell off after that, as his remaining eight appearances resulted in four TDs and zero top-15 fantasy outings. Darnold is entering his fifth pro season having yet to produce a top-25 fantasy campaign. In fact, he's yet to clear 20 passing TDs or 3,024 yards in a single season. Darnold is still pretty young (25), but he's a long shot to ever emerge as a fantasy option. He's nowhere close to the fantasy radar.

Bridgewater signed with Miami and will provide insurance behind third-year starter Tua Tagovailoa. Bridgewater won Denver's starting job last season and was serviceable (67% completion rate, 7.2 YPA), but that didn't translate to any fantasy success (one weekly finish better than 13th). Bridgewater has been around since 2014, but his best fantasy campaign was an 18th-place finish with Carolina in 2020. Even if Bridgewater replaces Tagovailoa, he's likely to cap out as a mid-range QB2. Consider the 29-year-old only in very deep superflex formats.

Minshew returns as Jalen Hurts' backup in Philadelphia. After tossing 37 TDs and 11 INTs during two seasons (23 games) in Jacksonville, Minshew played only two full games in relief of Hurts last season. One was a top-10 fantasy outing against a poor Jets defense and the other an 18th-place effort in a tough spot against Dallas starters in Week 18. Minshew's career efficiency is right around league average and he adds a little bit of value with his legs. He'd be on the QB2 radar if called on to replace Hurts, but that makes him appealing only as a stash in deep superflex formats.

Johnson was limited to 46 touches during his first two NFL seasons prior to being vaulted onto the fantasy radar in 2021. The 2019 UDFA was limited to only the occasional touch during most of last season, but he was essentially handed the keys to the backfield during three weeks in which Nick Chubb was out/limited. Johnson was impressive, reaching 24 touches, 130 yards and 20 fantasy points in all three games. The 26-year-old sports a 5.3 YPC (2.2 YAC) on 137 career carries and has been a factor as a receiver as well. Johnson has zero standalone value as long as Chubb and Kareem Hunt are active, but he'll be a priority waiver add if ever called upon for another spot start.

Bellinger was selected by the Giants in the fourth round of April's draft. He is an inline TE prospect who spent 61% of his collegiate snaps run-blocking (second-highest rate in this rookie class). In turn, he was limited to a 68-771-5 receiving line on 104 targets (9% share) during his four seasons. Bellinger proved a reliable target (three career drops), but most of his usage was in the short range. He's big, very young and showed well at the combine with a 4.63 40-yard dash (110 speed score ranked third at TE), 22 bench reps and a class-best 125-inch broad jump. The Giants' TE depth chart is wide open, but rookie tight ends rarely land on the fantasy radar. Bellinger shouldn't be drafted.

Granson played 217 snaps last season after the Colts selected him in the fourth round of the 2021 draft. Stuck behind Jack Doyle and Mo Alie-Cox, Granson was limited to 15 targets while primarily being utilized in the short area (4.0 aDOT). Alie-Cox is back for 2022, but Doyle's retirement opens the door for Granson to play a larger role, assuming he fends off rookies Jelani Woods and Andrew Ogletree. Granson was a de facto wide receiver in college and ranked near the top of the 2021 rookie TE class in aDOT and yards per reception. The SMU product has some receiving upside, so keep him stashed in dynasty.

Washington selected Bates in the fourth round of the 2021 draft. The Boise State product barely saw the field early in his career, but with Logan Thomas and Ricky Seals-Jones battling injuries, he was promoted to a major offensive role in the second half of the season. From Week 10 on, he played 74% of Washington's snaps, but was limited to an 18-238-1 receiving line on 24 targets and posted one fantasy finish better than 20th. Thomas remains the starter in Washington, but the veteran's early-season availability is in question as he recovers from last season's torn ACL. Bates is worth stashing in dynasty formats, but even if Thomas misses time, Bates is unlikely to land on the TE1 radar.

Otton was selected by Tampa Bay in the fourth round of April's draft. He enters the NFL after posting a 91-1,026-9 receiving line during 39 games at Washington. He lacks speed, but is a big, capable blocker and was effective as a short-area target for the Huskies, hauling in 91 of his 99 catchable targets (92%). Otton's efficiency took a big hit in his final season (28-250-1 in eight games), but a class-low 70% of his 46 targets were deemed catchable and he was almost exclusively a short-range target (ran a deep route a class-low 14% of the time). That led to a class-worst 5.4 YPT. It's a longshot considering the resume of rookie tight ends in fantasy, but Otton can be considered a deep sleeper with only Kyle Rudolph and Cameron Brate perhaps ahead of him on the Tampa Bay depth chart.

McBride was selected by Arizona in the second round of April's draft. A featured target in the Colorado State offense, he handled a massive 34% target share in 2021, which is tops in this rookie class across all positions. McBride produced a 90-1121-1 receiving line with nearly half of that damage coming in the intermediate area. The one TD is an eyebrow raiser, but seems fluky, as he scored on eight of 67 receptions the prior two seasons. McBride has the lowest drop rate in this class, having failed to secure only four of 234 targets. Down the road, he could emerge as an every-down player and one of Kyler Murray's top targets, but he simply isn't going to play much in 2022 barring an injury to Zach Ertz. Expect to see McBride on many 2023 breakout lists if Ertz is out of the way.

Dulcich was selected by Denver in the third round of April's draft. Dulcich is a seam-stretching receiving tight end who may not add much as a blocker in the pros. Dulcich was oft-used as a vertical target at UCLA, posting a class-high 12.9 aDOT during his four seasons. That led to a 17.6 YPR and class-best 11.1 YPT. He peaked with a 42-725-5 receiving line in 2021, which included a generous 21% target and 27% air yards share. Like nearly every rookie tight end in NFL history, Dulcich is a longshot for 2022 fantasy value and will likely operate as a situational player behind starter Albert Okwuegbunam. Of course, Dulcich could eventually emerge as the team's starter, so he's worth stashing in dynasty.

Moreau is entering his fourth NFL season and remains positioned as Darren Waller's primary backup. Waller was injured for seven games last season and Moreau played 95% of the snaps during those seven games. The results were not very inspiring, as he averaged 4.9 targets per game and ranked 22nd at tight end in fantasy PPG (7.7). Moreau has been effective when called upon (687 yards and 10 TDs on 79 career targets), but last season was an indication that he'd settle in as a TE2 -- not a must start -- in the event of a Waller injury. The 25-year-old is well off the fantasy radar.

Dissly signed a lucrative offseason extension to stay in Seattle, though he'll remain a situational player after the offseason acquisition of Noah Fant. Dissly flashed some fantasy appeal during his first two NFL seasons (2018-19), but injuries limited him to 10 games during the stretch. He's held up pretty well the last two seasons (31 of 33 possible games), but he simply hasn't been used much in the passing game (24-251-2 and 21-231-1 receiving lines). Dissly has nine touchdowns in four seasons and didn't even register an end zone target last season. With Fant atop the depth chart and Russell Wilson gone, Dissly isn't close to the fantasy radar.

Trautman enters his third NFL season yet to emerge as much of a factor in fantasy. The 2020 third-round pick seemed to be on the verge of a breakout around the midway point of last season, racking up a team-high 28 targets (18% share) during Weeks 8-11 before going down with an injury. However, he did that damage with Trevor Siemian under center. In six full games with 2022 starter Jameis Winston, Trautman averaged 2.0 targets per game. While we don't want to get tricked into extrapolating that four-game stretch in the box score, Trautman was a major receiving force in college and remains New Orleans' starting tight end. Hope remains for a third-year breakout, so the 25-year-old is a fine late-round flier in deeper leagues.

Huntley is back as Lamar Jackson's backup after replacing him for five games late last season. Huntley's output was a bit bizarre, as he had one huge game (four TDs and a position-high 35.9 fantasy points in Week 15), but four poor ones (total of one TD and 44.2 fantasy points). He averaged a massive 8.8 carries and 56.8 rushing yards per game in those five outings. Huntley, who went undrafted in 2020, has some insurance appeal due to his rushing prowess and the pretty good supporting cast in Baltimore. Of course, he won't see the field unless Jackson misses time, so consider stashing him only in superflex and dynasty formats.

Taylor signed with the Giants and will back up Daniel Jones. Taylor is now 33 years old and hasn't appeared in more than eight games in a season since 2017. He played four full games in Houston last season, none of which resulted in a top-10 fantasy finish. Taylor can still add some value with his legs (151 yards, 3 TDs last season), but he's an unproductive passer. Jones' durability woes add to Taylor's insurance appeal in superflex formats, but he has a very low ceiling.

Willis plummeted to Tennessee in the third round of April's draft. The Liberty product has a big arm and elite rushing talent, but his passing efficiency is a major concern. Willis struggled with accuracy (61% completion rate, 12.1% off-target rate), INTs (3.5% rate) and sacks (11.3% rate) last season, all of which were worst or second-worst in this class. On the other hand, he was aggressive (10.2 aDOT, 13.8 YPC) and a major factor with his legs (146-1227-13 rushing line, class-high 8.4 YPC). Ryan Tannehill is the Titan's clear-cut starter and that won't change as long as he's healthy and Tennessee is competing for a playoff spot. Willis is a developmental player with no short-term fantasy value, but he could some day emerge as a fantasy asset due to his rushing ability.

Love is entering his third season as Aaron Rodgers' backup after the Packers traded up to select him with the 26th overall pick of the 2020 draft. Love is obviously a major unknown and we haven't seen him play at a high level since 2018. He struggled in his final season at Utah State in 2019, tossing 20 TDs to 17 INTs and his off-target rate (15.5%) and QBR (51.7) were both worst in the 2020 rookie class. Love has a good arm, but his struggles with accuracy, turnovers and decision-making are concerns. There's long-term upside, but Love is no more than Rodgers insurance in the meantime.

Dalton signed with the Saints and will back up Jameis Winston this season. The 34-year-old hasn't played a full season since 2017 and he hasn't produced a top-15 fantasy campaign since 2016. Dalton played four full games for Chicago last season, none of which resulted in a top-12 fantasy outing. He threw five TDs and eight INTs during the span. Even if Dalton is called on to start this season, he'll barely be worth QB2 consideration.

After starting 15 games in place of Ryan Fitzpatrick last season, Heinicke will now revert to backup duties behind new Commanders starter Carson Wentz. Heinicke hung on the streaming radar with six top-12 fantasy outings through Week 11 last season, but the wheels fell off after that, as he failed to produce another finish better than 15th. The 29-year-old finished ninth at the position in rushing yards, but struggled to find the end zone (21 total TDs) and threw too many INTs (15). Heinicke is a backup and would be no more than a mid-to-back-end QB2 if he were to replace Wentz.
